    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-09-01T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-09-01T17:00:00-05:00" n="729"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">782.022/8–3150: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Turkey</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-09-01T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 1, 1950—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>122. <gloss target="#t_urtel1">Urtel</gloss> 149.<note n="1" xml:id="d729fn1"
                        >August 31, <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> Dept considers Turks must make own decision on minefield. While Dept was
                    willing furnish legal opinion this question on purely informal basis US cannot
                    take responsibility of urging Turks to lay minefield. Such urging might be
                    construed by Turks as indication US alarm Soviet intentions. Furthermore if
                    accident to shipping inadvertently resulted US by advising original laying of
                    mines might be considered to share responsibility. Dept suggests you advise Ad
                        Ginder,<note n="2" xml:id="d729fn2">The Ankara Embassy file copy of this
                        paper bears the notation: “I have shown this message to both Adm. Ginder and
                        Gen. Arnold; they will act accordingly, w[adsworth]. Sept. 19.” (Ankara
                        Embassy files, lot 57F72, box 2, 322.2 Straits 1950–52)</note> in his
                    capacity as technical adviser, point out to Turks delays involved in
                    establishment of minefield. Suggest you avoid, however, giving impression US
                    directly interested in influencing Turkish decision.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
